title: A Phase 3 Multicenter, Multinational, Randomized, Double-Blind, Placebo-Controlled Study to Evaluate the Efficacy and Safety of ALN TTRSC in Patients With Transthyretin (TTR) Mediated Familial Amyloidotic Cardiomyopathy (FAC)
description_brief: The purpose of this study was to evaluate the safety and efficacy of revusiran (ALN-TTRSC) in patients with transthyretin (TTR) mediated Familial Amyloidotic Cardiomyopathy. Dosing has been discontinued; patients are being followed-up for safety.

participantFlowModule.recruitmentDetails: A total of 206 patients with hereditary amyloid transthyretin (hATTR) cardiac amyloidosis were enrolled and randomized in the study.

adverseEventsModule.description: The same event may appear as both an AE and a serious adverse event (SAE). However, what is presented are distinct events. An event may be categorized as serious in one subject and as nonserious in another subject, or one subject may have experienced both a serious and nonserious event during the study

limitationsAndCaveats.description: While dosing of patients was discontinued early, a protocol amendment allowed additional safety follow-up visits. Per the new assessment schedule, this study did not meet the criteria of a Terminated study, as additional follow-up visits occurred.

explanation_target: Reason: The investigational agent revusiran (ALN-TTRsc) is an RNA interference (siRNA) therapeutic designed to reduce production of transthyretin (TTR) — i.e. it is a nucleic-acid biologic that directly targets disease-causing protein production rather than acting as a small molecule or symptomatic cognitive/psychiatric drug. citeturn0search0

Act (key details extracted): The trial is a randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled Phase 3 (ENDEAVOUR) program of revusiran for transthyretin (TTR)-mediated familial amyloidotic cardiomyopathy (FAC); revusiran was administered subcutaneously in the program but development/dosing was discontinued after an imbalance in mortality was observed and the program was terminated. citeturn0search2turn0search1

Web-search evidence (supporting sources): PubMed description of revusiran as a GalNAc‑siRNA targeting TTR; BioCentury and company filings reporting discontinuation of the Phase 3 ENDEAVOUR program due to a mortality imbalance and safety review; clinical trial listing showing the extension/safety follow-up after dosing stopped. citeturn0search0turn0search1turn0search7

Reflect: Classification decision — 'disease-targeted biologic' — is based on mechanism (siRNA reducing TTR production), which fits the developer-defined 'disease-targeted biologic' category (biologic that targets disease pathology). Note: this trial concerns hereditary TTR amyloidosis (cardiac) not Alzheimer’s disease; if you required only Alzheimer’s trials, this would be classified as 'N/A' for that purpose. citeturn0search0turn0search4
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational agent revusiran (ALN‑TTRsc) is an RNA interference (siRNA) therapeutic whose mechanism is to reduce hepatic production of the disease-causing protein transthyretin (TTR). This is a direct intervention on pathogenic protein production/aggregation (a proteinopathy). citeturn0search1turn0search0

Act: Key details extracted from the trial description — drug: revusiran (ALN‑TTRsc), a GalNAc‑conjugated siRNA targeting TTR mRNA; Phase 3 ENDEAVOUR was a randomized, double‑blind, placebo‑controlled study in TTR‑mediated familial amyloidotic cardiomyopathy (FAC). Dosing was subcutaneous; the program was stopped early because of an observed mortality imbalance. These facts support that the intervention acts on proteostasis/proteinopathy (TTR production). citeturn0search0turn0search2turn0search5

Reflect: Mapping to CADRO — the trial’s biologic directly lowers synthesis of a misfolding/aggregating disease protein (TTR), which corresponds most specifically to CADRO category I) Proteostasis/Proteinopathies. Although the disease is hereditary TTR amyloidosis (cardiac) rather than Alzheimer’s, the mechanistic class (modulating production/handling of a pathogenic protein) clearly fits CADRO I rather than other categories (e.g., inflammation, amyloid‑beta, or non‑therapeutic). If multiple distinct targets had been described, R) Multi‑target would be considered, but here the focus is singular (TTR). citeturn0search4turn0search1

Web search evidence (key sources): - Alnylam press release describing initiation of ENDEAVOUR and that revusiran targets transthyretin (TTR). citeturn0search0 - PubMed article describing revusiran as a GalNAc‑siRNA with mechanism (hepatocyte uptake, RISC‑mediated TTR mRNA destruction). citeturn0search1 - PubMed/Cardiovasc Drugs Ther. report of the Phase 3 ENDEAVOUR study and discontinuation after an observed mortality imbalance. citeturn0search2 - Nonclinical safety publication summarizing revusiran as a first‑generation GalNAc‑siRNA targeting TTR and noting program discontinuation. citeturn0search5turn0search4
